Published as an Artifact — link above. A quick rundown of the design decisions:

Concept: A single floating RTL Qt-style panel (~420px, matching a real desktop settings-panel width), with three semantically color-coded connection states doing all the communicating — no separate "brand" accent competing with them.

Palette — three trust-coded states, kept out of AI-cliché territory (no neon, no purple-gradient hero):
State A / محلي (offline, default) — muted emerald #157a4a — calm, reassuring
State B / متصل (online/search) — burnt amber #a3620a with a pulsing dot + glow ring on the hero card — deliberately "loud"
State C / سحابي (cloud handoff) — indigo-violet #5347c9
Neutrals are a cool-green-biased paper/ink (not pure grey or AI-cream), so they read as chosen rather than default.
Type: Tajawal (500 for body/labels, 800 for the title and hero message) — one Arabic-native family carried across every weight rather than force-pairing in a mismatched Latin face, since the product is Arabic-primary. The font is inlined as base64 @font-face data URIs (fetched and subset to Arabic+Latin), so it renders correctly — including the diacritic in "محلياً" — regardless of what's installed on the viewer's machine.

Interaction (fully wired, try it):
The Smart Internet Access toggle drives A↔B.
The External AI Handoff block is disabled and explained ("requires enabling internet access first") while offline — it only lights up purple once you're online, and turning it on is what triggers B→C plus the inline "encrypted snapshot saved" toast, styled in emerald (the local data stayed safe, even though you're going to the cloud — that color choice is deliberate).
قطع فوري (Instant disconnect) always snaps back to State A from anywhere, with a brief emerald flash confirming the lock re-engaged.
Both themes are designed (not inverted), and animations respect prefers-reduced-motion.
This is an HTML/CSS/JS mockup for visual review. If you want it translated into an actual PySide6 QFrame + QSS implementation (real QPropertyAnimation for the pulse/toast, QSS for the state palettes) to drop into the real desktop app, say the word and I'll build that next.

